.SH NAME
alias::module \- Alias one module as another
.SH VERSION
.IX Header "VERSION"
This document describes version 0.003 of alias::module (from Perl distribution alias\-module), released on 2023\-09\-30.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\& package Your::Alias::Name;
\& use alias::module \*(AqSome::Real::Module::Name\*(Aq;
.Ve
.PP
To avoid \fBrequire()\fR\-ing:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& use alias::module \*(Aq\-norequire\*(Aq, \*(AqSome::Real::Module::Name\*(Aq;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module aliases one module name to another.
.PP
.Vb 2
\& package Your::Alias::Name;
\& use alias::module \*(AqSome::Real::Module::Name\*(Aq;
.Ve
.PP
is equivalent to:
.PP
.Vb 6
\& package Your::Alias::Name;
\& BEGIN {
\&     $Package::Alias::BRAVE = 1;
\&     require Some::Real::Module::Name;
\& }
\& use Package::Alias \*(AqYour::Alias::Name\*(Aq => \*(AqSome::Real::Module::Name\*(Aq;
.Ve
.PP
except that this module does not use Package::Alias and is simpler. It is
useful if you want to let users access a module\*(Aqs functionality under a
different (usually shorter) name.
